                "To approach this problem, let's first recall some fundamental definitions and properties of tensors and matrix calculus.\n\n**Definitions and Properties:**\n\n1. **Trace**: The trace of a matrix \\( \\mathbf{B} \\), denoted \\( \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{B}) \\), is the sum of its diagonal elements.\n\n2. **Inverse**: For a square matrix \\( \\mathbf{A} \\), \\( \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\) is its inverse if \\( \\mathbf{A} \\mathbf{A}^{-1} = \\mathbf{I} \\).\n\n3. **Transpose**: The transpose of a matrix \\( \\mathbf{A} \\), denoted \\( \\mathbf{A}^T \\), is obtained by interchanging its rows with columns.\n\n4. **Determinant**: The determinant of a square matrix \\( \\mathbf{A} \\), denoted \\( \\det(\\mathbf{A}) \\), is a scalar value that can be computed from the elements of \\( \\mathbf{A} \\).\n\n5. **Matrix Differentiation**:\n\n   - **First-order derivative** \\( \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\) of a scalar-valued function \\( f(\\mathbf{A}) \\) is a matrix that, when multiplied by \\( \\Delta \\mathbf{A} \\) (a small change in \\( \\mathbf{A} \\)), gives an approximation to the change \\( \\Delta f \\) in \\( f \\).\n   \n   - **Second-order derivative** \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} \\) is a matrix that describes how the rate of change of \\( f \\) with respect to \\( \\mathbf{A} \\) itself is changing.\n\n**Solution:**\n\n**Part (a): Compute \\( \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\) and \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} \\)**\n\nGiven \\( f(\\mathbf{A}) = \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-1}, \\mathbf{A}^{-T}) \\).\n\n1. **First-order derivative \\( \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\)**:\n\n   - Recall that \\( \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-1}, \\mathbf{A}^{-T}) \\) uses the cyclic property of the trace, i.e., \\( \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\mathbf{A}^{-T}) = \\mathrm{tr}((\\mathbf{A}^{-T})^T \\mathbf{A}^{-1}) = \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-T} \\mathbf{A}^{-1}) \\).\n   \n   - Using differentiation rules for inverses and transposes, we have:\n     \\[\n     \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\mathbf{A}^{-T}) = -\\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\cdot \\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^{-T}}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}}) = -\\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\cdot -\\mathbf{A}^{-1}) = 2 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-2}).\n     \\]\n\n2. **Second-order derivative \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} \\)**:\n\n   - Differentiate the first-order result:\n     \\[\n     \\frac{\\partial^2 f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} (2 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-2})) = 2 \\cdot (-2) \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-3}) \\cdot \\mathbf{A}^{-1} = -4 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-3}) \\mathbf{A}^{-1}.\n     \\]\n   \n   - Alternatively, using Leibniz rule:\n     \\[\n     \\frac{\\partial^2 f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\left( 2 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-2}) \\right) = 2 \\left( -2 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-3}) \\cdot \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\right) = -4 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-3}) \\mathbf{A}^{-1}.\n     \\]\n\n**Part (b): Compute \\( \\frac{\\partial g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\) and \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} \\) where \\( g(\\mathbf{A}) = \\det(\\mathbf{A}) \\)**\n\n1. **First-order derivative \\( \\frac{\\partial g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\)**:\n\n   - The determinant function \\( \\det(\\mathbf{A}) \\) is related to the trace through the matrix's eigenvalues. The first-order derivative of \\( \\det(\\mathbf{A}) \\) with respect to \\( \\mathbf{A} \\) is \\( \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\).\n   \n2. **Second-order derivative \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} \\)**:\n\n   - Differentiating \\( \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\) with respect to \\( \\mathbf{A} \\):\n     \\[\n     \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} \\mathbf{A}^{-1} = -\\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\cdot \\mathbf{A}^{-1} = -\\mathbf{A}^{-2}.\n     \\]\n   \n   - Thus, the second derivative is:\n     \\[\n     \\frac{\\partial^2 g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} (\\mathbf{A}^{-1}) = -\\mathbf{A}^{-2}.\n     \\]\n\n**Summary:**\n- \\( \\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} = 2 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-2}) \\)\n- \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 f}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} = -4 \\mathrm{tr}(\\mathbf{A}^{-3}) \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\)\n- \\( \\frac{\\partial g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}} = \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\)\n- \\( \\frac{\\partial^2 g}{\\partial \\mathbf{A}^2} = -\\mathbf{A}^{-2} \\)\n\nThese derivatives are based on the properties of trace, determinant, and their relationships with matrix differentiation.",
